Lecture 12.1:Nutrition andMetabolism

BMEN920002

Jordan Chambers

jordanc@unimelb.edu.au

Learning objectives

  • Understand onutrition and the six major categories of nutrients
  • Explain othe processes involved in carbohydrate metabolism including glycolysis, anaerobic fermentation and aerobic respiration
  • Describe lipid and protein metabolism and how they interact with carbohydrate metabolismo
  • Suggested readingo
    • Saladin, Anatomy & Physiology: The Unity of Form and Function •9e
      1. 1•-26.4

Nutrition

  • Energy balance and body weight
    • When energy intake equals energy expenditure, body weight is stable
    • However, there is a homeostatic set point
      • Approximately 30-50% of variation is genetic, while the rest is environmental
  • Short-term regulators of appetite
    • Ghrelin is secreted by the parietal cells of the stomach, particularly when empty, to produce thefeeling of hunger and also stimulates the thalamus to secrete growth hormone-releasing hormone
    • Peptide YY is secreted by the enteroendocrine cells in the ileum and colon when food enters thestomach to produce the feeling of satiety
    • Cholecystokinin (CCK) is secreted by the enteroendocrine cells in the duodenum and jejunum toproduce appetite-suppressing effect and also stimulates the secretion of bile
    • Amylin is secreted by the pancreatic islets and produces the feeling of satiety

Nutrition

  • Long-term regulators of appetite work of periodsof weeks to years to regulate appetite andmetabolic rate
    • Leptin is secreted by adipocytes through thebody (in amounts proportional to the fat stores)and stimulates sympathetic nerve fibres, whichsecrete noradrenaline to stimulate lipolysis
    • Insulin is secreted by beta cells in the pancreasand stimulates glucose and amino acid uptakeand promotes glycogen and fat synthesis
  • Appetite regulation occurs in the arcuate nucleusof the hypothalamus largely by gut-peptides, butalso other mechanisms such as:
    • Gastric peristalsis
    • Chewing
    • Stretching of the stomach

Figure 26.2

Nutrition

  • Appetite is about how much AND what kind of food is to be consumed
    • Examples of neurotransmitters influencing kind of food are
      • Noradrenaline stimulates appetite for carbohydrates
      • Galanin stimulates appetite for fatty foods
      • Endorphins stimulate appetite for protein
  • Obesity is defined as a weight 20% more than the recommended
    • Excess weight shortens life expectancy and increases the chance of atherosclerosis, hypertension,diabetes, joint pain, kidney stones, gallstones and numerous cancers
    • Weight has a large genetic component, but a predisposition is often created in infancy/childhood byoverfeeding, which increases the size and number of adipocytes in the body
      • Number of adipocytes usually remains constant in adulthood, just changes in size

Nutrients

  • A nutrient is any ingested chemical that is absorbed and used by the body
    • Water, carbohydrates, lipids, proteins, minerals and vitamins
  • Many can be synthesized by the body, but some cannot (essential nutrients), such as
    • Minerals, most vitamins, 8 of the amino acids and 1-3 fatty acids
  • Water
    • Functions as solvent, coolant, reactant/product and many others
  • Carbohydrates and sugars functions include:
    • Fuel as it is easily oxidised to produce energy
      • Neurons and erythrocytes exclusively use carbohydrates (so blood glucose closely regulated)
    • Structural component of glycoproteins, glycolipids, ATP (GTP, cAMP,etc) and nucleic acids
    • Can be converted into amino acids and fats
      • Carbohydrates are stored as fats, but efficient oxidation of fats depends on the presence ofintermediates from carbohydrate metabolism
    • Dietary carbohydratescome in several forms (monosaccharides, disaccharides and polysaccharides)
    • Most dietary carbohydrates come from plants (grains, legumes, fruits and root vegetables)

Nutrients

  • Fibre
    • Refers to all fibrous materials that aren’t digested such as cellulose, pectin, gums and lignin
    • Water-soluble fibre (pectin) is important in lowering blood cholesterol levels
    • Water-insoluble fibre (cellulose) is important for assisting defection
  • Lipids
    • Fat is very important energy storage as it is less oxidised and hydrophobic
    • Important for the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins
    • Phospholipids and cholesterol are major structural components of plasma membranes, myelin,steroid hormones and bile acids
    • There are essential fatty acids (linoleic acid) that cannot be synthesised by the body
    • Source of dietary fat are meats, eggs diary products and some plant products such as coconut andpalm oils
    • Lipoproteins (tiny droplets of cholesterol and triglycerides coated in proteins and phospholipids
      • Classified as chylomicrons, high/low/very low density lipoproteins
        • Ratios indicate if cholesterol is being removed from the body, which is probably more to dowith dietary saturated fats rather than dietary cholesterol

Nutrients

  • Proteins
    • Proteins are important for muscle, cell membranes (receptors, pumps, channels), bones, cartilage,tendons, skin, hair, nails, hormones, enzymes, plasma proteins in blood
    • Can synthesize 12 out of 20 amino acids, so there are 8 essential amino acids
    • Dietary sources include animal proteins (meat, eggs, dairy) and plant proteins (beans, rice, legumes,cereal)
      • Need to ingest more plant proteins for the same nutritional requirements, but also considervitamins, minerals, fibre and saturated fats
    • Nitrogen balance is determined by rate of nitrogen ingestion and the rate of excretion
  • Minerals
    • Make up about 4% of the body mass, largely calcium and phosphors in bones and teeth
      • Calcium, iron and magnesium are important cofactors for enzymes
      • Chloride is important for stomach acid and mineral salts function electrolytes
    • Best sources are vegetables, legumes, milk, eggs and fish

Nutrients

  • Vitamins
    • Letters were assigned in order of discovery, so beware of chemical names (e.g. ascorbic acid is vitaminC)
    • Water-soluble vitamins can’t be stored in the body and are important for synthesis of blood,connective tissuesand as coenzymes
    • Fat-soluble vitamins can be stored and, therefore, levels can get too high
      • Important for eye, epithelium, bones/calcium and blood

Carbohydrate Metabolism

  • All oxidative carbohydrate is glucose catabolism:C6H12O6+ 6 O2=> 6CO2+ 6H2O
  • Requires enzymes to remove hydrogen, which are transferred tocoenzymes
    • Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+)
    • Flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD)

Figure2.31

Carbohydrate Metabolism: glycolysis

Figure26.5

Carbohydrate Metabolism:Anaerobic fermentation

  • Occurs when oxygen is not available (or cells withoutmitochrondia)
  • NADH donates a pair of electrons to pyruvate, hereby producing lactate and NAD+
    • The production of NAD+is required for glycolysis
  • Lactate will leave the cell and go to the liver
    • The liver will oxidize lactate back to pyruvate when oxygen is available

Carbohydrate Metabolism:Aerobic respiration

  • Generates the most ATP
  • Occurs in the mitochondria
    • Matrix reactions
    • Membrane reactions

Glycogen Metabolism

  • Glycogenesis is the synthesis of glycogen
    • Glycogen synthase attaches a glucose to growing polysaccharide chain
    • Stimulated by insulin
  • Glycogenolysisis the hydrolysis of glycogen to release glucose
    • Performed by the enzyme glycogen phosphorylase
    • Stimulated by glucagon and adrenaline
  • Gluconeogensisis the synthesis of glucose from glycerol and amino acids
    • Occurs in the liver
    • Can also occur in the kidney
